				<td colspan="2"><span>Bard  epic is definitely not a gimme.  I understand your situation as I was once in it as well.  I was the GL of a small/medium size guild.  While we were able to finish some of the easier epics (shaman, druid, monk) we just couldn't seem to get quite enough for a Trak raid.  I understand the desire to stay in your guild with your friends, but most people eventually see the need to move on to the higher level guilds.  Eventually myself and all my officers ended up leaving our guild and joining one of the larger ones in the game.  I didn't do this for my epic per se, I did it for the same reason my officers did.  Unless you either build your guild up to be a uber force on your server or join an existing uber guild, the odds are rather good that you will never see any of the high end game that EQ has.  It sucks, but that's the way the game was designed.  I didn't want to leave my friends, but I didn't want to end up leaving this game without ever having seen some of the bigger mobs/zones.
<br />
Yep I got my epic now, and I got Nature's Melody off of Tunare.  But it really wasn't about the loot, it was about the fun of doing those new things and seeing those new zones.  BTW, as a bard you haven't lived til you went on a PoG raid.  Your guild isn't clearing the guardians to get to Tunare without you.  It's one of the few times where as a bard you feel absolutely needed.  Just my 2 cents, but don't be afraid to move on to another guild.  You pay for the game, why not see it all?  And if your friends are truly friends, they will understand and maybe even join you.  Besides, you can always hang out with your old guild when your new guild isn't raiding. /shrug
<br />

<br />
Mylec Jhalavar Vile Virtuoso Extraordinaire
<br />
Solusek Ro
